-- Cemex, Credicorp, Itau, Lan Air, Petrobras: Latin America Equity Preview
-- Andres R. Martinez
-- 2010-07-09T03:48:18Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-07-09/cemex-credicorp-itau-lan-air-petrobras-latin-america-equity-preview.html

          
          
             The following companies may have
unusual price changes in Latin American trading. Stock symbols
are in parentheses and share prices reflect the previous close.  
 The  MSCI Latin America Index  gained 0.7 percent to 3,850.
In Brazil, preferred shares usually are the most-traded class of
stock.  
 Brazil  
 Petroleo Brasileiro SA  (PETR4 BZ): The state-controlled
company said it refined a record 2 million barrels of oil a day
on July 3. The shares rose 0.7 percent to 27.58 reais.  
 Usinas Siderurgicas de Minas Gerais SA  (USIM5 BZ) and  Vale
SA  (VALE5 BZ) entered into two agreements for transporting
steel and iron ore. One contract was for the movement of steel
products from the state of Minas Gerais to Sao Paulo and will
last six years, and Usiminas forecast savings of 1.9 million
($1.1 million) reais a year from the pact.  
 Separately, Vale workers at two Ontario plants voted to end
their year-long strike, the United Steelworkers union said in an
e-mail. Vale, the world’s largest iron-ore miner, rose 0.2
percent to 39.01 reais. Usinas, Brazil’s second-largest
steelmaker, gained 1.4 percent to 52.92 reais.  
 Chile  
 Lan Airlines SA  (LAN CC): Latin America’s largest airline
by market value said system passenger traffic for June increased
15.5 percent as capacity rose 15.4 percent. Lan’s shares rose 1
percent to 10,677 pesos.  
 Mexico  
 Cemex SAB  (CEMEXCPO MM): Latin America’s largest cement
maker said it agreed to sell quarries in Kentucky for $90
million to help pay debt. The shares fell 1.1 percent to 12.28
pesos.  
 Cia. Minera Autlan SAB  (AUTLANB MM): The largest manganese
producer in North America said net sales more than tripled in
the second quarter. Autlan rose 3.7 percent to 27.44 pesos.  
 Peru  
 Banking stocks: Peru’s central bank raised its benchmark
lending rate for a third consecutive month yesterday to prevent
the faster-than-forecast economic recovery from stoking
inflationary pressures. The reference rate was increased by a
quarter point to 2 percent, matching the forecasts of all 17
economists surveyed by Bloomberg.  
 Credicorp Ltd.  (BAP PE) rose 2.7 percent to $94.  Intergroup
Financial Services Corp.  (IFS PE), owner of Peru’s fourth-
largest bank, gained 2.9 percent to $21.10.  
